00:03:02.600 --> 00:03:09.279
So one of the first questions I see over on Slido is, what are the benefits of preparing

00:03:09.279 --> 00:03:13.679
these APIs in Python versus R?

00:03:13.679 --> 00:03:19.479
So I would say there's sort of the one main reason, which is you have Python users versus

00:03:19.479 --> 00:03:23.880
R users, and that's, I would say, the main reason you should decide to use one or the

00:03:23.880 --> 00:03:28.919
other, or you're using a Python library versus an R library.

00:03:28.919 --> 00:03:35.080
So I would say for most data science applications, that's enough, basically.

00:03:35.080 --> 00:03:38.520
If you have Python users, you're working with Python users, then having something all in

00:03:38.520 --> 00:03:39.520
Python is really handy.

00:03:39.839 --> 00:03:44.800
That's one of the main reasons to use Shiny for Python versus Shiny for R. They do mostly

00:03:44.800 --> 00:03:48.639
the same stuff, but if you're working with Python users, it's helpful.

00:03:48.639 --> 00:03:55.320
The one area where that's not quite true is in the API level.

00:03:55.320 --> 00:03:59.559
And the main reason for that is that Plumber as an API is a wonderful tool.

00:03:59.559 --> 00:04:03.479
It's a great way of deploying our things to an API.

00:04:03.479 --> 00:04:07.080
But the usage of Plumber, for the most part, is pretty small scale.

00:04:07.080 --> 00:04:13.000
And so as a result, it hasn't been sort of battle-tested at these very large or very

00:04:13.000 --> 00:04:18.959
fast APIs, whereas tools like some of the Python API tools like FastAPI are really developed

00:04:18.959 --> 00:04:22.279
around sort of very, very high-performance production APIs.

00:04:22.279 --> 00:04:27.880
And so you do end up with a lot of benefits of...

00:04:27.880 --> 00:04:31.000
You get a lot of the benefits of those tools just by using them.

00:04:31.000 --> 00:04:37.760
So an example of that is the way that FastAPI does the data validation.

00:04:37.760 --> 00:04:43.279
So when you sort of specify, like, this is the object type I want to accept, and I want

00:04:43.279 --> 00:04:47.279
to give you a 422 error if you're providing a JSON that's malformed or something like

00:04:47.279 --> 00:04:48.640
that.

00:04:48.640 --> 00:04:54.679
That's both very smooth from a developer perspective and also incredibly technically impressive

00:04:54.679 --> 00:04:56.279
with how fast it is.

00:04:56.279 --> 00:04:59.839
So you're able to deploy those APIs, have them be very, very high traffic, and still

00:04:59.839 --> 00:05:03.000
that type checking happens extremely quickly.

00:05:03.000 --> 00:05:06.119
But I would say for most data scientists, there's no particular difference in terms

00:05:06.119 --> 00:05:07.959
of what you're likely to do with it or not.

00:05:07.959 --> 00:05:12.959
It's mostly, are you a Python user or an R user?

00:05:12.959 --> 00:05:15.959
Thank you.

