00:07:25.940 --> 00:07:31.140
I saw a few questions around SageMaker.

00:07:31.140 --> 00:07:35.380
So I just wanted to make sure we addressed one of these two.

00:07:35.380 --> 00:07:39.380
But one was, we mainly use AWS for our infrastructure.

00:07:39.380 --> 00:07:44.179
What is the benefit of using Posit solutions for an end-to-end workflow and production

00:07:44.179 --> 00:07:46.179
in comparison to SageMaker?

00:07:46.459 --> 00:07:49.059
Yeah, so this is a really hard question.

00:07:49.059 --> 00:07:54.220
I would recommend probably talking to somebody on the sales team to just figure out your

00:07:54.220 --> 00:08:02.579
particular use case and whether Posit solutions are helpful or duplicative or not necessary.

00:08:02.579 --> 00:08:08.220
One thing I have experienced is around cost and the way that SageMaker or other sort of

00:08:08.220 --> 00:08:14.339
managed cloud solutions charge you, which is mostly they charge a markup on compute.

00:08:14.339 --> 00:08:19.619
So if you're using SageMaker and you're using some EC2 instance with a particular amount

00:08:19.619 --> 00:08:27.100
of RAM and CPUs, you're usually charged, I think, 20, 30% above the AWS rate for that.

00:08:27.100 --> 00:08:32.580
And that's kind of the charging for the convenience of having those things be managed for you.

00:08:32.580 --> 00:08:35.900
Whereas Posit solutions all run on a licensing model.

00:08:35.900 --> 00:08:40.380
So you're charged by the number of users, but you can run it on whatever compute you

00:08:40.380 --> 00:08:41.380
want.

00:08:41.380 --> 00:08:43.739
If you have your own server, you can run it there or your own cloud.

00:08:44.140 --> 00:08:50.580
So basically you're paying from the compute side of things, like the basic AWS fee.

00:08:50.580 --> 00:08:52.460
And that fee is also capped, which is nice.

00:08:52.460 --> 00:08:56.460
So if you have one server that's running connect, that means that no matter what your data scientists

00:08:56.460 --> 00:09:01.380
throw at that server, they're not going to suddenly explode your costs around that.

00:09:01.380 --> 00:09:03.940
And you don't have to worry about cost caps and things like that.

00:09:03.940 --> 00:09:05.900
It's just basically we have the server, we budget it for it.

00:09:05.900 --> 00:09:07.539
You can do whatever you want there.

00:09:07.539 --> 00:09:11.299
If you outgrow that server, you have to come and have a budgeting conversation with whoever

00:09:11.299 --> 00:09:13.580
runs your infrastructure.

00:09:13.580 --> 00:09:17.979
So those can be big deals or not, depending on your use case.

00:09:17.979 --> 00:09:24.219
One sort of big advantage of AWS SageMaker is scaling, scaling things up is a lot easier

00:09:24.219 --> 00:09:25.219
on that system.

00:09:25.219 --> 00:09:30.260
But again, this is really context dependent about whether these things matter to you or

00:09:30.260 --> 00:09:31.260
not.

00:09:31.260 --> 00:09:35.099
So I'd recommend talking to sales.

00:09:35.099 --> 00:09:41.260
And if it's helpful to add, we do have lots of customers who run on AWS today, but also

00:09:41.419 --> 00:09:46.299
with regards to SageMaker, we'd have customers running Posit Workbench through SageMaker

00:09:46.299 --> 00:09:47.619
as well.

00:09:47.619 --> 00:09:52.419
So I did just put in the chat the little short link I made if you wanted to schedule time

00:09:52.419 --> 00:09:59.099
to chat with the team, because they can go into that in more detail too.

00:09:59.099 --> 00:10:01.820
Let's see.

00:10:01.820 --> 00:10:11.059
Question over from Tyrone in YouTube is, how do you manage different Python or Cordo versions

00:10:11.059 --> 00:10:14.099
major and minor versions on Connect?

00:10:14.099 --> 00:10:16.780
Is it inadvisable to host multiple versions?

00:10:16.780 --> 00:10:17.780
Would it affect publishing?

00:10:17.780 --> 00:10:20.859
Yeah, you should definitely host multiple versions.

00:10:20.859 --> 00:10:25.859
So Connect lets you, both Connect and Workbench let you, the administrator, basically specify

00:10:25.859 --> 00:10:29.200
the same way you can do with R. You can specify these are all the different Python versions

00:10:29.200 --> 00:10:31.500
that you have up there.

00:10:31.500 --> 00:10:36.539
The one big difference, I think, between R and Python in terms of multiple versions is

00:10:36.539 --> 00:10:41.219
that the Python, it's really important that the major versions match exactly, whereas

00:10:41.219 --> 00:10:46.659
R you can kind of get away with not quite matching exactly, because our package ecosystem

00:10:46.659 --> 00:10:50.859
is a little bit more backwards compatible than the Python one.

00:10:50.859 --> 00:10:56.539
So what I have done is basically you have a sort of upgrade path for your team in terms

00:10:56.539 --> 00:11:01.820
of Python, where you're sort of saying, these are the Python versions we're supporting.

00:11:01.820 --> 00:11:04.419
Everybody needs to use one of those Python versions when they're deploying, and you have

00:11:04.419 --> 00:11:08.020
those Python versions also installed on Connect.

00:11:08.020 --> 00:11:14.539
And then if you do that for both Python and Cordo, it's the same problem, same basic problem,

00:11:14.539 --> 00:11:17.599
then the matching will happen pretty well.

00:11:17.599 --> 00:11:21.820
One other really crucial thing for Python is to have people use virtual environments

00:11:21.820 --> 00:11:29.059
when they're publishing, because basically when you publish something to Connect for

00:11:29.059 --> 00:11:33.859
Python, it basically checks the environment that you're running that in, and if that's

00:11:33.859 --> 00:11:37.059
like a global Python that you've just installed every package in the world onto, it's going

00:11:37.059 --> 00:11:41.559
to try its best to install those, because it has no way of really knowing what you need,

00:11:41.559 --> 00:11:44.059
and there could be lots of conflicts or just slow deploys from that.

00:11:44.059 --> 00:11:46.859
So I would say the number one thing is making sure people use virtual environments, and

00:11:46.859 --> 00:11:51.760
then the second one is trying to get some sort of upgrade path for your whole team who's

00:11:51.760 --> 00:11:57.380
using that system to make sure that they're using a supported version of Python.

00:11:57.380 --> 00:12:01.700
And you need to communicate that and organize it, but it's a helpful thing to do anyway,

00:12:01.700 --> 00:12:06.539
because there's not just Connect that runs into problems of Python versioning.

00:12:06.539 --> 00:12:10.419
Thank you.

00:12:10.419 --> 00:12:16.340
So jumping back over to Slido, there was a question that was, I must have missed it,

00:12:16.340 --> 00:12:20.739
but how was the custom Python package pushed to PositPackageManager?

00:12:20.739 --> 00:12:25.900
Oh, so this one, I actually didn't push it to PositPackageManager, because it's a public

00:12:25.900 --> 00:12:29.500
package, so I could just install it from GitHub.

00:12:29.500 --> 00:12:33.580
So for pushing things to PositPackageManager, there's a number of different ways.

00:12:33.580 --> 00:12:38.859
The one that I think is probably the best one is to have a kind of Git-backed, basically

00:12:38.859 --> 00:12:41.500
Git-backed deployment to PackageManager.

00:12:41.500 --> 00:12:45.700
So basically, PackageManager is, I think it has a GitHub source.

00:12:45.700 --> 00:12:48.460
It's been a long time since I've done this.

00:12:48.460 --> 00:12:54.140
And then whenever you push something to GitHub, PackageManager will pull and build it.

00:12:54.140 --> 00:12:57.539
In this case, it's such a small package that, and since it was public, it was just easier

00:12:57.539 --> 00:13:03.500
to have it on GitHub.

00:13:03.500 --> 00:13:07.739
If we have a link to that, too, it might be helpful, Ryan, if you wouldn't mind sharing

00:13:07.739 --> 00:13:09.739
that in the chat, too.

00:13:09.739 --> 00:13:10.739
Yeah.

00:13:10.739 --> 00:13:14.940
And that'll give you a lot of the great benefits of package versioning and having it only be

00:13:14.940 --> 00:13:18.539
installed, having Connect set up to install from there, probably.

00:13:18.539 --> 00:13:22.299
So there's a lot of advantages of that system, I just didn't quite have time to get it all

00:13:22.299 --> 00:13:23.299
set up.

00:13:23.859 --> 00:13:30.739
I see Michael asked a question in YouTube as well, and it was, any recommendations for

00:13:30.739 --> 00:13:33.500
alternatives to PyLance?

00:13:33.500 --> 00:13:35.979
And sorry if I don't know that one yet.

00:13:35.979 --> 00:13:40.820
Not having PyLance on Posit Workbench VS Code is a huge pain, to the point I often develop

00:13:40.820 --> 00:13:43.820
on my personal machine and then upload to Workbench.

00:13:43.820 --> 00:13:44.820
Yeah.

00:13:44.820 --> 00:13:51.780
So basically, Microsoft, which owns VS Code, has a number of extensions that are usable

00:13:51.780 --> 00:13:59.940
only on the closed source version of VS Code, and Workbench runs the open source version.

00:13:59.940 --> 00:14:03.619
So there's a number of open source type checkers that are similar, I think the one that most

00:14:03.619 --> 00:14:06.419
people use is PyRite.

00:14:06.419 --> 00:14:13.940
But yeah, so it's kind of, and I think also, that's probably the one that I most often

00:14:13.940 --> 00:14:21.659
hear about, and Shiny Live, which is the WebAssembly hosted Shiny for Python that uses PyRite for

00:14:21.739 --> 00:14:22.739
type checking.

00:14:22.739 --> 00:14:25.739
It works really well.

00:14:25.739 --> 00:14:28.739
Thank you.

00:14:28.739 --> 00:14:37.099
So another question over from Slido was, you mentioned the setup is best for proof of concepts.

00:14:37.099 --> 00:14:40.859
What are the constraints of this setup if we wanted to use it for serving many models

00:14:40.859 --> 00:14:42.580
for production?

00:14:42.580 --> 00:14:45.299
Yeah, so there's a few of them.

00:14:45.299 --> 00:14:49.140
So one of them is, and I kind of mentioned this in the project readme, I don't think

00:14:49.140 --> 00:14:53.859
I quite emphasized this enough on the video, which is that kind of endpoint authorization

00:14:53.859 --> 00:14:55.619
pattern.

00:14:55.619 --> 00:14:59.580
That works great to protect against mistake or people doing the wrong thing.

00:14:59.580 --> 00:15:04.739
I wouldn't say that it's reliable against a malicious user, right?

00:15:04.739 --> 00:15:09.059
So if you were to publish this to the world, you'd want to, first of all, take out any

00:15:09.059 --> 00:15:13.940
of those, the model upload endpoint, have those hosted on some other API that's controlled

00:15:13.940 --> 00:15:19.299
at the top level through something like PositConnect or another gateway.

00:15:19.299 --> 00:15:25.020
I would say there's nothing technical about that API where you wouldn't serve it.

00:15:25.020 --> 00:15:26.219
You wouldn't have that be a score.

00:15:26.219 --> 00:15:32.140
And this is, again, one of the advantages of FastAPI is that the API technology is strong

00:15:32.140 --> 00:15:38.619
enough to serve, commonly used to serve very large intensive production workflows.

00:15:38.619 --> 00:15:43.940
I would say the main thing that I would think about is, are you the person to deploy and

00:15:43.940 --> 00:15:45.539
host a production API?

00:15:45.539 --> 00:15:48.619
Is your team able to do that?

00:15:48.619 --> 00:15:52.500
And if yes, then that's great.

00:15:52.500 --> 00:15:56.820
You can do it and work fine, but it often is a different set of skills in terms of building

00:15:56.820 --> 00:16:00.820
an API that can scale the way you need it to scale, can be cost effectively run.

00:16:00.820 --> 00:16:04.859
Some of those things are things that oftentimes you don't necessarily have on your team or

00:16:04.859 --> 00:16:07.140
personally.

00:16:07.140 --> 00:16:14.820
The one other, and then the one last feature is, I would be worried about using the same

00:16:14.820 --> 00:16:22.500
environment, I think both for licensing reasons and other reasons, to use the same environment

00:16:22.500 --> 00:16:30.539
to serve internal data products and external ones, both in terms of just people making

00:16:30.539 --> 00:16:34.739
a mistake and publishing the wrong thing to the public API when they meant to publish

00:16:34.780 --> 00:16:40.299
to the private API and something getting out there, or running into basically performance

00:16:40.299 --> 00:16:44.219
problems if you have a big spike in usage on the external one.

00:16:44.219 --> 00:16:49.619
That's not always the case, but just something I tend to favor personally is to have just

00:16:49.619 --> 00:16:52.900
separate environments where you can still definitely use Connect.

00:16:52.900 --> 00:16:58.380
We have people who use Connect for serving large public listings, shiny apps or APIs,

00:16:58.380 --> 00:17:00.539
like that would work fine.

00:17:00.859 --> 00:17:06.859
You would probably want to have two to make sure that the data sources and things you

00:17:06.859 --> 00:17:11.260
were publishing to Connect were actually accidentally exposed.

00:17:11.260 --> 00:17:14.180
That's not necessarily a technical thing, more of a person-people thing of just making

00:17:14.180 --> 00:17:20.300
sure that if you have a database with a bunch of PII, you want to make sure that the public-facing

00:17:20.300 --> 00:17:24.339
thing cannot read from that database and you have a network wall between them, because

00:17:24.339 --> 00:17:26.540
people will always make mistakes.

00:17:27.540 --> 00:17:35.540
Okay, so we have a few-is it okay if we go a few minutes over the top of the hour?

