Let's see.

00:18:02.300 --> 00:18:10.939
One of the questions I didn't ask yet from Slido-let me just copy over.

00:18:10.939 --> 00:18:16.260
Not a question I like to ask, but I want to ask every question that comes in here, but

00:18:16.260 --> 00:18:19.540
one was, how would someone implement this workflow without Connect?

00:18:19.859 --> 00:18:25.739
Yeah, so the nice thing about-one of the things I really love about Connect is that Connect

00:18:25.739 --> 00:18:30.459
doesn't have any-the applications that you deploy to Connect are not special Connect

00:18:30.459 --> 00:18:32.699
versions of those applications, right?

00:18:32.699 --> 00:18:37.939
So this FastAPI or this Shiny app, they're not special Connect FastAPIs, they're just

00:18:37.939 --> 00:18:44.680
vanilla Shiny and Connect and FastAPI applications, and so that means you can host them wherever

00:18:44.680 --> 00:18:45.680
you want to.

00:18:45.680 --> 00:18:50.760
You can do the same workflow with multiple servers that you're managing or a single server

00:18:50.760 --> 00:18:54.800
running several processes.

00:18:54.800 --> 00:18:58.199
The advantage of that, of course, is that you don't have to pay for the software, right?

00:18:58.199 --> 00:18:59.199
It's obvious.

00:18:59.199 --> 00:19:05.920
The disadvantages, I think, are the-there is a cost associated with rolling your own

00:19:05.920 --> 00:19:14.439
stuff, and the cost is you're now responsible for the security, patching, and deployment

00:19:14.439 --> 00:19:16.719
workflows, and that can be pretty expensive.

00:19:16.719 --> 00:19:20.119
It's just not something you necessarily pay for right away.

00:19:20.119 --> 00:19:26.199
The kind of good example is that sort of same one of just your compliance or security group

00:19:26.199 --> 00:19:31.359
upgrades the requirements on what you need to do, like I had an experience where my company

00:19:31.359 --> 00:19:35.959
was going through this big process of using a different encryption algorithm because of

00:19:35.959 --> 00:19:40.319
some of the people we were trying to sell to, and this was an enormous task for all

00:19:40.319 --> 00:19:43.920
the services that we had rolled our own, but when we were sort of checking on Connect,

00:19:43.920 --> 00:19:48.199
like Connect had already implemented that in a previous version, so it was just a flag.

00:19:48.199 --> 00:19:51.359
So it's kind of like-I kind of think of like these software licensing tools as a little

00:19:51.359 --> 00:19:57.239
bit like a commitment device to continue to upgrade and patch your stuff, like improve

00:19:57.239 --> 00:20:04.040
what it is, and that's the cost is that you have a lot more responsibilities around all

00:20:04.040 --> 00:20:07.479
the things that you're hosting, and that can be a really good decision depending on the

00:20:07.640 --> 00:20:13.239
team, your budget, how much money you have versus like the expertise in running those

00:20:13.239 --> 00:20:18.040
services, or it can be a really, really painful decision if you go the other way where you

00:20:18.040 --> 00:20:21.520
commit to rolling your own services, but then you discover down the road you have these

00:20:21.520 --> 00:20:25.319
big security gaps that you didn't know about, and that can be pretty difficult.

00:20:25.319 --> 00:20:30.680
Okay, let's see.

00:20:30.680 --> 00:20:36.839
One more question over from Slido was Docker and Kubernetes were mentioned in the presentation.

00:20:36.839 --> 00:20:41.760
Could you talk a little bit more in detail about how these technologies help the management

00:20:41.760 --> 00:20:44.119
of the API or app?

00:20:44.119 --> 00:20:48.800
Yeah, so I would say Docker-so there's two pieces of it.

00:20:48.800 --> 00:20:53.040
So Docker is basically a way of capturing like more of the environment.

00:20:53.040 --> 00:20:58.680
So when you do Connect deployment, Connect captures like your Python environment, but

00:20:58.680 --> 00:21:03.560
it's running-like all the Connect applications are running on the Connect server, so if that

00:21:03.719 --> 00:21:09.560
has like a particular system library installed, it's going to need to use that system library.

00:21:09.560 --> 00:21:13.959
Docker basically lets you have those things be customized, so it makes your deployment

00:21:13.959 --> 00:21:18.239
a little bit more-like it's more work because you have to deal with the Docker file.

00:21:18.239 --> 00:21:22.239
Docker is a little bit more irritating of a development experience, but the benefit

00:21:22.239 --> 00:21:26.920
is that more of the things like your Linux version, you know, your libgirl version, like

00:21:26.920 --> 00:21:30.359
those things are all locked down to a particular application.

00:21:30.359 --> 00:21:35.560
And then Kubernetes is a way of scaling Docker instances horizontally, so running like many

00:21:35.560 --> 00:21:40.040
Docker instances on one or many servers.

00:21:40.040 --> 00:21:44.680
And so I would say they're kind of like growth patterns from this would be what I would sort

00:21:44.680 --> 00:21:48.959
of say, like, and I think Vetiver does a-is a tool which does a great job of like helping

00:21:48.959 --> 00:21:53.339
you get those sort of like basic API Docker containers written for you.

00:21:53.339 --> 00:21:57.719
But oftentimes, like it's-if you have something where you have an API, it's pretty easy to

00:21:57.719 --> 00:22:01.599
put it into a Docker container because there's a lot of patterns which is like, how do I

00:22:01.599 --> 00:22:02.599
run fast API in Docker?

00:22:02.599 --> 00:22:08.319
And you just go copy that and point to your API and it works fine.

00:22:08.319 --> 00:22:14.359
Docker is a really good solution, I think, for passing things on to a DevOps group.

00:22:14.359 --> 00:22:17.800
So if you-if you're a data scientist and you're trying to get something deployed in production

00:22:17.800 --> 00:22:23.000
or in another system, you can say to say like, look, I have this version running on Connect,

00:22:23.000 --> 00:22:25.280
you can go test it, try it out, see how it works.

00:22:25.280 --> 00:22:27.040
And I also have a Docker file for you.

00:22:27.040 --> 00:22:29.439
So you just need to go and take this and put it on your system.

00:22:29.439 --> 00:22:33.400
Most things have some way of running and exposing a Docker container.

00:22:33.400 --> 00:22:37.160
So it's a really nice way of just doing people's work for them a little bit.

00:22:37.160 --> 00:22:38.920
And it's not that hard to do.

00:22:38.920 --> 00:22:44.079
But if you don't have to use it, I wouldn't, I would say it'd be my advice, like, if you

00:22:44.079 --> 00:22:46.920
can have something where it's like, oh, yeah, I can get this working and deploy it and stuff

00:22:46.920 --> 00:22:47.920
like that.

00:22:47.920 --> 00:22:52.359
Like, start with that and then worry about Docker when you actually have Docker problems.

